    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-11-08T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-11-08T06:00:00-05:00" n="246"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d246">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.24/951: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Hanoi</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Reed</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hanoi</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-11-08T18:00:00+07:00"
                            >November 8, 1940—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 8:59 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>34. Reference my telegram No. 32, paragraph 1, today’s date, 10 a.m. This
                    afternoon it was agreed that the Texas Oil Company may reexport certain
                    stipulated petroleum products providing loading is done under combined French
                    and Japanese supervision. Details of the extent of this supervision are to be
                    worked out between Texas Oil Company manager and French and Japanese officials
                    at Haiphong and whether the demanded supervision will be too onerous is as yet
                    unknown.</p>
                <p>Sent to Cavite for repetition to the Department, Chungking, Peiping, Hong Kong,
                    Shanghai, Canton.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Reed</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
